text:
not long left to get applications in to volunteer at our fab new daytime drop-in in #eastbourne. help us to support survivors in your area. get in touch to learn more!
.
.
we are currently recruiting self-identifying women aged 21 and over to volunteer at our new women-only daytime drop-in in eastbourne.

if you have good listening skills, lots of empathy, a non-judgemental attitude, an interest in supporting survivors and can spare 3-6 hours a month on thursdays please contact katie or liv (contact information below) for more info & for an application pack.

no experience necessary as full in-house training is provided. closing date friday 23rd november 2018, interviews will be held on thursday 6 december.

training dates are as follows:
10am-3pm thursday 10th/17th/24th/31st january 2019 in eastbourne. 
trainees will need to attend all 4 days.

we welcome applications from all sectors of our diverse community and applications from older women, bme or lbt women are particularly encouraged.

contact details: info@survivorsnetwork.org.uk // 01273 203380

text:
this is indira summerville, a senior at morristown high school and president of melanin minds, a multicultural and social activism club. this is how she feels about the current political climate, ahead of tomorrow's elections. â€œtired. that would be one word i would use to describe my emotions toward the current political climate.

i am tired of having to yell â€œblack lives matterâ€ every time i see an african american man being killed by those who swore to protect us, to ensure their names and faces would not be forgotten.

i am tired of having to type #metoo to keep men out of influential positions after  sexually harassing and assaulting unsuspecting women.

but, despite my fatigue at the young age of seventeen, i know that as an african american young woman, such action is not only necessary for the country, but is necessary for me to survive and thrive. this is why i am politically active: because i know the implications of staying silent.â€

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates suppoed by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

text:
a lot of women, (and until recently myself included) have found it difficult to accept love. 
we grew up hearing that we could do anything.  we learned how to run change a tire, get a degree and hang our own shelves. 
we learned that people hurt us. 
so when someone offered their live whether it be a friend or a beloved we ran the other way. 
we could attach to animals, animals were easier. 
we could attach to jobs, jobs couldnâ€™t hurt us. 
until they did. 
and then people still found a way to get in

so many women i talk to feel alone.  we may know how to change a tire, lead a board meeting and travel alone but do we know how to surrender into a friendship? 
it actually makes perfect sense.  finding ways to go it alone is the perfect response for what you have been through and how you survived. 
thatâ€™s not a character flaw, thatâ€™s a response that actually was completely appropriate for the time. 
and if you still feel like itâ€™s hard to connect then itâ€™s time to heal.  animals and jobs are awesome. 
and intimacy is possible.  and it doesnâ€™t have to be snot crying in therapy.  it could be fun ðŸ˜Š

is it time to connect?  is it time to find loving nurturing safe friendships and relationships?  then the measure of success to love and to receive love doesnâ€™t seem like an unattainable cosmic joke.  it seems like the next thing possible ðŸ§šâ€â™€ï¸

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

what a beautiful course. the beauty of the day, my husband and my round were the only things that held it together yesterday.
i tried to be friendly and it backfired. 
i noticed a guy that was in the group allowing us to play through was a member of a course in the city that i teach a lot of gentleman at. when i told him that he found it funny and laughed and looked at me and said â€œyou teach?â€ disgusted, i walked away. 
back up on the green, he made a snide comment to my husband after he unfortunately missed a 10 foot putt and said â€œnice lag.â€ then i made my 5 footer and he looks at michael and says â€œwoah i guess this girl can playâ€ and starts laughing again. what is it that is so troubling that women can be good at golf? so michael looks at him and said â€œwe yes, she is a professional.â€ he then laughed again and rolled his eyes. michael asked him why he found it funny and the guy could give no answer. 
fast forward to hole 11. i teed off and a guy out on his patio yelled over at michael and says â€œoh haha did she outdrive you?â€ well, iâ€™m super aggressive on that hole and hit my ball over the tree line landed 30 yards from the green. since i have vowed to be done with taking this bs i responded by saying â€œyes and iâ€™m about on the greenâ€ to which he also found funny. 
iâ€™m done taking this crap. iâ€™ve taken it for too long. 
if you donâ€™t like something that someone says to you. be inspired by #metoo . speak up!

text:
***link in bio***
here is text that took a whole lot of courage and distance to write. this piece is about internal change after trauma. it speaks to those who have been through sexual violence, harassment and shame. please take your time to read and share the love

extract : "three years after the aggression, two years after love struck my world, i put myself in the position where i had to face my present, my very real and present transformation. because one night i was hurt, disappointed, and lost, i went seeking my past into the arms of a man i knew was wrong for me. going straight into the pit, i knew it was no good, but i thought i could handle it, i thought iâ€™d be okay, as iâ€™ve always been when it came to men and sex. the night finished, awfully, and the morning began even worse. that is when i took the bus, pouring out the realisation of my deepest change : i should act depending on what i feel profoundly, not act to cope or to run away from something. if it means not acting, then be it. i let myself go, and i wept like a child, learning how to listen to my truth as if it was the most devastating and most beautiful music iâ€™ve ever heard." #metoo #believewomen #trustwomen #healing #trauma #medium #writer #journalist #womenwhowrite #makebridges #community #change #transformation #mtl #montreal

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the start.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing for the 2016 election.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the content and more or less fake accounts - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking the responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole thing is build on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
it's been over a year since i've posted anything in my blog, but today i finally broke my hiatus.
i've been holding onto this post for several months; going back and forth in my brain about whether or not i should share it. 
was i ready?
today i finally decided to publish it. i haven't shared this story with anyone except close family and friends. this link to the first blog in a series of three is up on my profile if you'd like to check it out.
no, i didn't relapse. but i discovered something that i know if i wasn't strong in my recovery i probably would relapsed. 
#edrecovery #eatingdisorderrecovery #metoo #timesup #trauma #newblog

text:
v for vendetta (2/8) "remember, remember, the 5th of november..."
as the world is going towards a direction that seems to speak only words of hate, that seems to have as its one and only purpose to strip away human rights from as many people as possible, and as we approach here in new york an election day that feels as crucial as it ever has, i feel like sharing this old monologue i recorded from v for vendetta.
because only love can make us fearless. and if we don't learn to love each other, to protect each other, to support and have hope for each other, even for those we don't know, there will be no tomorrow, no hope, and no light to beak through these dark, dark days.
and, once again: for all the times i've been told to "mind my own business", because "what's an actor to do with politics?", to be careful, because "you don't want to take sides", for all the times they tried to shut me up because "these angry women are hateful and unattractive", for all the times i've been told to "go back to my country", for all this and more, tomorrow november 6th go vote.
and you know what? as a human being, a citizen, an immigrant, as a woman and as an artist, as a free person and an activist, this is exactly my own business and i will keep minding that. and no, i won't stop taking sides. i will keep choosing what to give my voice to, and if you don't agree with it, fine. but you won't shut my mouth, you won't stop my song if freedom with your words of hatred.
#5thofnovember #vforvendetta #agirlfromtheislandinnewyork

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin

cnn

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
jupiter entering sagittarius is like a much needed cavalry charging in to help the wounded and battered, yet still determined battalion of warriors.~
~
sagittarius is the natural home of jupiter, and so this is where he can most feel expansive, joyful, and abundant.~
~
jupiter, in all his abundant mass and size, is also the giver of many gifts, and so these qualities are likely to radiate outward.~â€¨â€”â€”~â€¨jupiter entered scorpio last october, and within a week the #metoo movement began. and then for the past year jupiter in scorpio has been tearing through and exposing all of the deepest, darkest, and most painful secrets of the collective. for many, this was experienced on a personal and familial level as well.~
~
necessary work, but really only palatable in short bursts.~
~
these final days of jupiter in scorpio are a good time to reflect on that which was stirred up for us. how have we grown? what did we process and transcend? what did we learn? how are we more complete and whole now? and what can now we let go of?~
â€”â€”~
thankfully, jupiter will enter sagittarius on november 8th. and with that will almost certainly bring a lightening of the energy, both collectively and personally.~
~
with jupiter in sagittarius, we can reconnect with our innate joy of living. we can be more exuberant and jovial. we can reconnect with a sense of humor.
with jupiter in sagittarius we might be gifted with greater perspective, a horizon-like view of our lives. and from that, we might be gifted with greater understanding and acceptance.~
â€”â€”~
exactly what jupiter in his home sign might bring will look different for everyone of course, and below is an outline of what to expect from jupiter transiting each house of the natal chart. heâ€™s transiting at least one of these houses for you, wherever sagittarius falls in your chart.~
~

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the start.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing for the 2016 election.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the content and more or less fake accounts - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking the responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole thing is build on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
part of #healing and moving through feelings of #guilt and #shame is finding allies, people who #inspire and remind you of your #beauty and divine #nature. healing is the heart of the many global movements for #reparations and #decolonization.

healing is the polar opposite of what most of the world's political and business leadership seek to sell. hence the title of this article, which speaks to my own sorry experiences over the last four years.

#googleprotectssexualpredators.

if you know me and my work, you know that i write a lot about guilt and shame as currencies. i also talk about using them to fund healing projects such as a #migratinguniversity and #decolonialbusinessacademy. itâ€™s true.

while iâ€™d rather not shame and guilt people and companies into giving monies, we need the cash. i do. just read my last article, $6.42 and the dream. believe me, i don't want to remember the how and why of how google has been protecting one sexual predator that i know by name and many others such as andy rubin, but sometimes we can't forget or move forward without a formal reckoning and financial reparations.

that's what #metoo and #timesup and #niunamenos and #balancetonporc represent: reckoning and reparations.

sometimes we experience situations where healing can most fully happen when financial and material resources are available. #decolonization and #reparations are not metaphors. they are #economic relationships that promote love, healing, and #resilience. that's why i see guilt and shame as global currencies. may they soon go out of fashion, just like #fastfashion.

iâ€™m looking for $500k to fund a free and open migrating university and decolonial business academy. this school will teach people how to design and elevate businesses that heal us as individuals and diverse peoples who share a global ecosystem in transition. the method at the heart of the work is called decolonial bizness world, and you can learn it by watching this video here, on youtube, which is one of hundreds of companies that google aka alphabet owns.

#decolonialbiznessworld is made for the #magicians of the global #economy, those of us who have been forced to the margins....

text:
#metoo and #timesup and #niunamenos and #balancetonporc represent #reckoning and #reparations.

sometimes we experience situations where healing can most fully happen when financial and material resources are available. #decolonization and #reparations are not metaphors. they are #economic relationships that promote love, healing, and #resilience. that's why i see guilt and shame as global currencies. may they soon go out of fashion, just like #fastfashion.

iâ€™m looking for $500k to fund a free and open migrating university and decolonial business academy. this school will teach people how to design and elevate businesses that heal us as individuals and diverse peoples who share a global ecosystem in transition. the method at the heart of the work is called decolonial bizness world, and you can learn it by watching this video here, on #youtube (link in bio), which is one of hundreds of companies that #google aka #alphabet owns.

#decolonialbiznessworld is made for the magicians of the global economy, those of us who have been forced to the margins of capitalist accumulation, while serving its masters and everyday beneficiaries. we have been made marginal even as we remain the global majority.

decolonial bizness world is also made for allies, for people who see truth through delusion and violence and are willing to put their money where their mantra lives.

curriculum for the migrating university and decolonial business academy will focus on geologic, #native, and local living histories. in other words, where in the world are you? who has lived in that place over the years, centuries, millennia? what kinds of people live there today? now, based on your answers, what does that place need to more easily weather #climatechaos, resist #proudfascism, and create #belovedcommunity?

dr. martin luther king, jr. defined beloved community as one made of people coming together for racial healing, #peace, and shared wealth. decolonial bizness world uses stories and symbols to teach everyday business operations such as #accounting, distribution, and #marketing from the standpoint of ecological resilience and beloved community....
name: darshan elena campos

text: if you know me at all you know i love wonder woman.  she is strong and she is mighty, she is smart and she is beautiful, she knows what is right and inherently sees the good in people and in this world, and she fights for what she believes in.  for a long time i never felt i could wear her armor because i didnâ€™t deserve to represent her, or that somehow i hadnâ€™t earned the right.  my children made me feel differently this year.  itâ€™s time, they said.  i am strong, smart, and beautiful.  i care about this world and the people in it, and i know the difference between what is right and what is wrong.  i wear the cuffs of the amazons as a reminder of what i too have been through so that i may never forget the abuse i have suffered at the hands of men that thought they deserved better than me or that their life was more important than my own.  i let that oppression weigh me down for a long time, but that time has passed.  this is the end of the line for those who presume that their existence is more valuable than that of their neighbor, their brother, their sister, daughter or mother.  for my children and the other children of tomorrow, i vote.  #takethepowerback #sickandtired #metoo #wonderwoman #vote #endofline  and thank you @summerriordon and @hudwashere for allowing me to see my inner wonder woman each and every day through your eyes you are two wonderful examples of all that is good in this world

text: not how i felt today...went for a run and felt like i was gonna  be attacked. running the riverside trail and a man in a big truck was passing. i smiled politely and he grinned back and drove off. a few minutes later i saw him again looping a corner. i quickly scanned the path and no one was around. â€œwhy is he still here? is he following me? he must be. no one else is on this path. should  i turn around?â€. i kept going. he got on the the highway and disappeared. but my heart was still racing and i noticed how much fear i was in. just going for a freakin run and feeling like this? wtf? the sad thing is that this guy was likely just a friendly dude. but like many (including myself) this is what we feel like...way to often. so! to all you  amazing men out there....help us create a safe space. speak up. when you hear something , say something. be an example for the men to come. we need you.  and you need us. #togetherwerise

text:
well, after 8 days of the scad savannah film festival and so many wonderful films, here are my top picks! welcome to the caroline choice awards!

academy award ready - blackkklansman (this film better be on the oscar list. i canâ€™t begin to describe how amazing this film is.) most relevant film - the hate u give (another oscar film. amandla will be known as one of the greatest actresses of our generation. a difficult film to watch, but so valuable.) favorite line - green book (i wonâ€™t spoil anything by telling you the line, but the most memorable line in the entire festival comes from this film. go see it on november 21.) best foreign film - roma (a long film, but worth watching. another oscar contender.) unexpected film - the parting glass (a vulnerable, personal film. the humor follows directly upon the drama, which keeps the film from being too heavy. i hadnâ€™t heard of this film before, and it turned out being one of my favorites.) strongest relationship film - ben is back (a beautifully difficult film about substance abuse. the relationship between the mother and son is heartbreaking.) best short film - believe her (an insightful look into the difficulties women face after assault with doubt, accusations, and more. amazing that this film was developed before the #metoo movement began.) best silent film - geoff (lovely cinematography and locations with a compelling story. i would love to see this short as a full length feature someday.) #savannahfilmfestival #topfilms #film #acting #actor #director #blackkklansman #thehateugive #greenbook #thepartingglass #roma #benisback #believeher #geoff #shortfilm

i voted for the 11 jews killed while worshipping in the synagogue. for the african americans gunned down in the grocery store who barely got news coverage because it happens to them every day.  for the trans girl who doesnâ€™t know if sheâ€™ll even be able to speak about her own gender much less use the appropriate bathroom. for the children separated from their parents and put into cages. for the immigrants being arrested because being human is now illegal. for the rape victim that deserves access to a safe abortion. for the countless women who have told their #metoo stories with such ferocity even though they know these men walk free. for the muslim woman who gets harassed when she goes into public in her hijab. for the single mother on welfare who doesnâ€™t know where their next meal is coming from. for the gay teenager who got disowned by his family and is living on the streets. for the school children that will never come home because they got gunned down in class. for every marginalized group in america. i see you. i hear you. i stand with you. ðŸ’™

t-1. itâ€™s been a year since #metoo and timesup took off, joining the womenâ€™s march as key moments and movements in the fight for womenâ€™s rights. at this point in time, the fight has been heavily centred around holding men to account for instances of inappropriate behaviour, sexual harassment, sexual assault, and worse.â£
â€¢â£â£
during the presidentâ€™s own campaign, numerous stories emerged of his less-than-favourable views on women: from grabbing women by the pussy, to saying women needed to be treated like shit, to saying americans would never elect carly fiorina because of her face. and that time he said women should be punished for having abortions, or when he said heâ€™d date his own daughterâ€¦ the list goes on.â£
â€¢â£â£
it should have come as no surprise, then, when the party that supported this man threw their weight behind the supreme court nominee accused of sexual assault and sexual misconduct by multiple women. nor should it have been a surprise when this nominee won the votes he needed to be confirmed to a lifetime on the supreme court. â£
â€¢â£â£
what both men have illustrated is that if youâ€™re white, male, privileged, and have gop support, no number of sexual misconduct allegations will bar you from the most powerful positions in the land. â£
â€¢â£â£
many believe that the #metoo movement hasnâ€™t gone far enough; that the reckoning facing those men who have been forced to resign or answer questions in court does not amount to justice for the crimes of which theyâ€™re accused. what is astounding in this context â€” at least to those of us at sowhat â€” is that 40% of americans believe the #metoo movement has gone too far. this chasm in opinion isnâ€™t influenced by gender as much as by party-affiliation: republican voters are more likely to believe the movement has gone too far, while democratic voters are more likely to believe it hasnâ€™t gone far enough â€” regardless of gender.â£
â€¢â£â£
at sowhat, we firmly believe that democracy is for the people by the people; this can only happen if the representatives in government are able to represent the best interests of the electorate.â£

text:
hi. please vote tomorrow, wherever you are across this bonkers nation, so sentient balls of glitter like myself don't have to return to being scared in public and scratch and claw for our rights again. even though we are more mainstream and visible than ever, that doesn't mean it's easy living.
.
gay or trans panic is still an admissible defense in court in most states in cases when people murder the lgbt+. adoption is either impossible or very difficult almost everywhere.  even our right to marry is under attack again. not everyone is a cis straight white christian, karen!!! and it's unamerican to think people have to live like you to be free!
.
and that's only lgbt+ issues! think of everything people of color are facing. low income people. native americans. flint, michigan. puerto rico. and women!!!! we continue to reward predators and abusers, especially politicians, even in the #metoo movement, and reproductive rights have never not been under attack. the gender pay gap is a blight.
.
the most common things i hear from people who choose to not engage are 1) that they aren't enthused by candidates - this speaks volumes on ignorance to your own privilege and shows that you very rudely don't understand that it's the responsibility of the majority to protect the rights of the minority, and 2) that the system is corrupt and it doesn't matter what you do, it won't change. you sound like a wacko conspiracy theorist, and here's the thing - the system can change. the best thing about our government is that it is changeable. we can achieve amazing things. we have before, to correct great ills our very country has wrought. it can and will happen again, but guess what we have to do to attain a system that works for everyone - show up in the first place. yes, of course it sucks now (always has depending on who you're asking?), but that means it just takes a teensy bit of effort to fix it.
.
this is our country. let's act like it.
.
ps - come to my 30th birthday prom this friday, 11/9 at 8pm @ lucky jack's lounge. if you like voting for your local, state, and federal candidates, you'll love voting for 1 of my potential 13 prom qing candidates!!! photo by @derekbishopmusic

text:
walk strong women. join us as we hit the trail this sunday from 12:30-5:30 henry cowell sp.  contact me to reserve your spot. 
a journey of empowerment, healing and community for survivors of sexual abuse and assault.  join us on the trail as we examine the impacts of assault on our minds and souls and discover ways to redefine ourselves as the resilient and strong women we are. we will take time to listen, reflect and move feeling strong and renewed. open to women of all ages. must be able to hike 5 miles over the course the day along rolling trails.

this event is being offered at no cost by darci morris, asw.  darci is an associate clinical social worker who specializes in grief, loss, trauma, and transition. she is the creator of life hikes providing outdoor opportunities for healing and personal growth.  darci is an associate therapist at clear minds integrative mental health in los gatos, ca offering traditional therapy, ecotherapy (outdoor based) and life coaching.  for more info contact her at 
lifehikessc@gmail.com

text:
while #metoo is a way to unite survivors in standing up against sexual assault and abuse, countless factors shape our individual experiences...
...from the circumstances of the acts committed against us...
...to the ability to escape or not...
...to whether we report and what happens when we try...
...to the resources available as we try to recover...
...to the behavior of those around us as we share our stories...
...to whether reporting or recovering or sharing is a luxury we can afford in the first place.
.
.
i've been ruminating on that. i hope you will, too.
.

text:
ðŸ™ŒðŸ¼ðŸ”Š #awesome #thisisamerica #winning #betofortexas #payitforward #howitsdone #vote #makeadifference â€” early voter turnout in this year's midterm election in #texas has reportedly surpassed the total voter turnout in the state's 2014 midterm election.
-
according to the texas tribune, over 4.5 million people in texas cast in-person ballots in this year's early voting period and more than 360,000 people have cast mail-in ballots in 30 counties alone.
-
of those counties, which the tribune noted is where the vast majority of registered voters in the state reside, nearly 40 percent of the 12.3 million residents in those counties that are registered vote have already done so. -
the preliminary data gathered from those counties via the texas secretary of state's office show that in the 12 days of early voting in the state, those 30 counties already surpassed voter turnout from not only the previous midterm election in 2014 but also early voting turnout for the 2012 presidential election in the state.
-
the report comes as republican sen. ted cruz continues to face a tough reelection challenge from democratic rep. #betoorourke in the closely watched texas senate race.
-
o'rourke said on friday that he believes the massive turnout of voters indicates he may be on the verge of becoming the first democrat to be elected to statewide office in texas in over 20 years.
-
"if north texas continues to turn out in the record numbers that we've seen, shattering every midterm total for as long as we've been looking at them, in some cases rivaling presidential voter turnout, then we're going to win this race," o'rourke said after a rally friday, according to the dallas morning news.
-
"the best thing i can do is continue to be with the people of north texas, just as we have been for almost the last two years," he continued.
-
though texas hasn't elected a democrat to the senate in decades, a number of polls have pointed to a narrowing margin between both candidates.
â€”

text:
happy 20th trauma anniversary to me. ðŸ™„ next one is in a week. ðŸ˜‘ these are the only trauma dates i know (i have several traumas) and didn't even know these ones until a few days ago when i started to feel a need to start putting on paper what happened with this guy and when. i found my calendar from 20 years ago (i was 14) and started to read it and write everything down. only then i realized it's my trauma anniversary in a few days. that day is now here as it's way past midnight. probably because i've been going through it all, in detail, during the past few days, i've been doing really shitty tonight. like really shitty. bring on the super puffy eyes when i wake up! it felt like it came out of nowhere and i thought and feared it would never end. it took its time and finally ended. for now at least. in a way i feel such deep sorrow towards so many things i have lost because of all the things that have happened to me. but i guess grieving is healthy. even after 20 years. or 19. 25. or 34-24. 
#ptsd #cptsd #ptsdawareness #cptsdawareness #trauma #traumaanniversary #sexualabuse #mentalhealth #mentalillness #mentalhealthawareness #metoo

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text: â€œthis verse is dedicated to me, myself and i...â€ â¤ï¸â¤ï¸â¤ï¸ i write a lot for others. iâ€™m hella motivated to inspire, from my students to my friends to complete strangers, but i must confess i had been neglecting my inner child for a long time. she spoke to me loud and clear last month, demanding that i pay attention to the ways she had to survive. she asked me to take notice, so that i can learn to let go of the survival tactics, the patterns of settling for less, the rage loops...my inner child was confused by the ways she was harmed. the pain sent her reeling and stifled her intuitive power. she only wanted to be acknowledged. iâ€™m prioritizing my mental health from this point forward because i have the desire to fully embrace my moment to thrive. thank goodness for the gift that is tenderness towards oneself. please remember to take care of you. #youmatter #selfcare #selfcarefirst #mondaymotivation #womenrappers #lyricsmatter #blackgirlmagic #fr333us #brujalyfe #metoo #oakland #oaklandrap #bayarea #acapella #straightbars

i've always hated this body
the bumps on my skin
with stretch marks imprinted on
curves i've never asked for

all this flesh i carry around
never felt like my own
another's sick obsession
another's gratification

crowded places scare me
being one in a sea of sweating flesh
my hips are but an ignorant prod
my breasts are bust a hasty nudge

i've lost my voice
my sanity 
somewhere 
in those crowded places

where another woman stands
enduring what shouldn't be
calculating.
reacalculating.

but never letting a sound slip.

i guess i've failed her too. ~hazel ðŸ–¤

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
"the first time he put his hands on me, i had confronted him because another girl told me she'd "been together" with him. i was very intoxicated that night. i hit him in the face and turned to run away when he grabbed me by my neck. his nail scratched my neck and left a mark. i was so scared and crying, then after that he was holding me and telling me he was sorry. i knew i was wrong for hitting him, but he would later tell me that i "opened the door" for him to start hitting me.
.
.
we lived together for about three months, and the abuse got worse. he liked to drink and use cocaine, so during those times is when the violence was the worst. he would hit me in my face, hit my head against the door, threaten me with a knife, and stomp on me with his shoes on. i can also remember times when he would call me the b-word, spit on me, and tell me to kill myself. i couldn't believe the same man who told me he loved me could treat me that way." . . Â© amanda
.
.

text:
#metoo #essexpfcc #policeconduct #eleanor4epping lies vs truth: 
20 years ago jane pullum and  jay remney thomas had engagement party @ jon pullum = brother = our home: 42 south view road, loughton. night b4 stayed over, jay want 2 bring 1 kilo cannabis in house. i said no, locked front door key. drugs put jane's car boot - jay: "cos i'm such a face - my audi tt will get done". jane nails, hair next day. jay tells jon (i hadn't) drugs in jane's boot. square up 2 each other. jay's criminal guests "this is jane & jay's house" - feud: jay "i'll keep coming for you, forever". jane tells their mum "drugs were jonathan's" = jon not speak 2 dad last 2 years his life cos jane's lies. upset jon deeply. jay beat jane up twice. 1st  badly. jane pregnant. had 2 abort = itp illness = similar sickle cell disease. jay coked up: angry about abortion - drag jane out bed by hair, down long hallway, stairs. kneeling on her chest (broken leg = cast), slamming her head on wooden floor. got call: jon tore 2 ilford police rape unit. jane drop charges. next time hit her, car chase = pushing her off road 2 loughton police station. jay smash jane car up on police forecourt - no cctv available - got off: community service. jon furious week later delivering national newspapers he printed @ west ferry printers when jay's motorbike on jane's driveway, he'd stayed over. jay = total bullshitter, con man, and worse some. georgina burrell and lisa morgan both very aware @ time it happened and now also #skypapers #maxwell #kath #robert_elms #ifoundmaxwell #printingcharity #bbcradiolondon #bbclondonnews #bxinfo #newsprinters #broxbourne #thenewsbuilding #newsuk #newsassociates #teamna #nctj_news #the_jdf #discovery

i've been learning the freedom in letting go.

letting go of intrusive thoughts, negative emotions, false beliefs about myself and others and the pain others have caused me. we all know this isn't an easy thing to do, or discipline to practice. what's the alternative? holding grudges, unforgiveness, anger and regret. this only negatively affects your mental health and steals happiness from your life.

healing isnt easy. living a healthy life isnt easy. but it's worth it. i'm a living testimony!

text:
the goddess said, rise up babe, what happened wasn't your fault. i will no longer give any power to the fuck ups of my past, i was *not* okay then, i was severely traumatized by the violence against my person by folks who i considered my own. that would cause anyone to go off kilter. i dont remember everything i said or did but i know i regret a lot of it. thank you to my community for still loving me the way that i was, cos i didn't, but i'm accepting myself now, and loving me hard cos i been through some rough ass shit! i wish i could go back in time and protect myself from the abuse but i had to learn from the pain, to grow from the shame and now, to reclaim my name. 
#owningmycrazy #absolutelybonkers #recoveringfromabuse #offkilter #fuckviolence #herenow #strength #courage #thegoddesslovesme #fucktheshame #metoo #itsnotmyfault #sorry #notsorry

text:
i just had 45 minutes to kill at union station, and happened upon a store called â€œamerica!â€ i have to give it credit- on the eve of the election midway through the first term of donald trumpâ€™s presidency, it has to be one of the very few places from sea to shining sea that is openly attempting to bring all americans together amidst the environment of bitter partisanship that has marked the past two years. no matter how you feel about the state of the countryâ€™s politics, there is something for you in america!

in america! you can buy a shirt with president trump triumphantly standing on a tank in front of an explosion, or a shirt depicting the president as a poop emojiâ€” conveniently set up next to the maga hats, as well as fake currency with trumpâ€™s face on the hundred, million, or billion dollar bill. 
if you want to jump ahead and show your support for the next presidential election, in america! you can purchase a shirt supporting former first lady michelle obama (who has given no inclination she will be running), or president trump on a ticket with vladimir putin, the leader of a nation whoâ€™s interests can be considered hostile to our countryâ€™s. 
if you donâ€™t want to buy something to broadcast your feelings about the current president, america! has many more options for you to show your national pride: a shirt honoring abraham lincoln by representing him riding a grizzly bear, holding the gettysburg addressâ€” a speech rallying devotion to the american cause to prevent those lost in combat from having died in vain, and a combat rifleâ€” similar to those used to take so many innocent american lives in recent years; a dish towel to proudly share your feminist identity in your kitchen, or a shirt with the face of fictional president frank underwood to show off your feelings towards the #metoo movement. 
if youâ€™d rather celebrate the history of our country you can buy presidential pez dispensers, and have the former commanders in chief help with a fix of refined sugar...needless to say, in america! there are more items to buy than could ever be highlighted in a single post.

the only thing missing in america! is any type of reminder to vote in tomorrowâ€™s election.

in new york, california, texas, and 27 other states you can take time off from work to vote
â€”
if you're wondering whether you can come in late or leave work early to cast your vote in the 2018 midterm elections on november 6, the short answer is, it depends on where you work.
â€”
see slide 5 ðŸ‘ðŸ¼
or
full detailed list:
www.businessinsider.com/can-i-leave-work-early-to-vote-2016-11
â€”
currently, there is no federal law that mandates employers provide their employees time off to cast their ballots. but the majority of us states have time-off-to-vote laws, also referred to as voter-leave laws, and have different requirements and exceptions for employers and employees.
-
while some states guarantee paid time off, for example, others do not. and the time guaranteed for employees to vote varies state-by-state as well.
-
of course, your own employer may offer leave to vote, even if your state does not. in 2016, for example, patagonia announced that would close all us stores on election day in an effort to encourage customers and employees to vote.
-
but, since not everyone's employer is so generous, you'd be well-advised to learn about the specific voter leave provisions in your state before the midterms.

#dontmess has become the rallying cry of my high school alums who supported fellow grad dr. christine blasey ford in the senate building on the day of her â€œhearing.â€ it has followed us in the days and weeks since as we protested in front of the capitol, on the steps of scotus, and around the country inspired by her and on behalf of survivors and then on behalf of an ever-expanding list of those whose voices need to be amplified. her courage is our courage, and courage is contagious. ðŸ’ª

the #dontmess campaign began when 3 members of our alumni group read, in a press conference with @kirstengillibrand and @maziehirono, the letter of support for dr. blasey ford that over 1,000 of @holtonarms alumnae signed and that was entered into the congressional record. during the presser, @alexis.goldstein held up at the podium a navy t-shirt that she has kept for over 20 years, since she was the age of dr. blasey ford at the time of her assault, a shirt that the holton field hockey team has made that said holton-arms on the front and donâ€™t mess on the back. her next words echo loudly for me, even 6 weeks later:
* donâ€™t mess with dr. christine blasey ford
* donâ€™t mess with the alumni of the holton-arms school
* but most importantly, donâ€™t mess with survivors because this is not 1991, and america has their back

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

#metoo  #shetoo  #himtoo #women_empowerment 
#fight for #harassment #debate
#its_time_to_change 
welcome to:

1. the first ever open mic on #metoo in lucknow
2. thousands of women using the #metoo hashtag online, the campaign has led to the creation of a list of academics accused of sexual harassment and assault. presenting the online campaign offline with student participation. 
3. if he can, then she can too. first time ever open mic not only for her but for him as well. presenting the untold stories of the male victims. 
4. bringing the lawyers and social activist together for providing the legal assistance and support to survivors.

ek kahani apki jubani 
the untold story of #metoo

presented by legal orbis and jashn

mark the date - november 11, 2018
time- 3:30 to 7:30

sheros hangout cafe

their is no registration fee. give your confirmation on 8840161960, 9696863087.

come join us and express your untold story, poetry and experience.

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

the guardian

text:
remembering the times that i would hope
that one day my pain will just disappear
and maybe even feel an ounce of true happiness 
until one day i woke up numb
so i tore my skin apart 
to know that this a reality iâ€™m living in
to feel something 
then the attacks come 
i stay down until the war calms down
im a broken soul that preaches positivity 
i say: â€œit will get better, it takes time, please be kind to yourself, itâ€™s all about self-loveâ€ but turn around and put myself to shame
having sleepless nights because i donâ€™t deserve to sleep
starving myself because itâ€™ll help you loose weight 
feeling and hearing my body beg for love and attention 
going through this alone wasnâ€™t my choice before
but iâ€™ve gotten used to the cold empty room
so i stay silent to protect the feelings of others
staying silent is me avoiding the reality
but no one cares 
so why should i?

nor sheep nor kine were near; the lamb was all alone,

text:
"i was eleven. my family went to a water park where there was a big wave pool. during one wave i got separated from my mom, so i was going back to her when i felt somebody's hand on my groin. when i looked up, i saw an uncle (older than my dad) just smiling in a disgusting manner. then my mom came, but i didn't tell her anything. i was shocked. but i should have because the man did the same thing to me again after ten minutes", remembers @arushiaishwarya from #hyderabad

if you have also faced street sexual harassment, please share your story with us. #hewonttease

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
as the rest of india, celebrates diwali, the festival of lights. the eastern part of our country , worship the fiesty dark goddess kali. she is the raging form of a diety who has killed the demons & has a garland around her head of the skulls. till she is stopped midway in her raging tornado by shiva. suddenly kali realises she is standing on shivaâ€™s chest & in a moment of realisation & shame she sticks her tongue out. 
goddess kali epitomises the darker, tantric side of hinduism. as the waning moon enters a new phase of the lunar calendar. we appease our goddess with meat and rice at her altar. 
india is also recently witnessing history among women, reincarnated as kali with the #metoo campaign. 
no one is sitting silent anymore for the unreported cases of gender atrocities in workplace or the street anymore. 
i see kali emerging today and behold her. she is daring to break the glass ceiling and slay her perpetrators. 
and like this cycle of nature, there is light and dark. 
to this unstoppable rage and silenced voices. i salute the diety in you and me. let the dark rise out of its slumber. only to emerge the light within. 
happy kali pujo and festive greetings for diwali.
#kalipujo #diwali #moodymo #fashionblog #fashionblogger #travel #bangalore #delhi

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

text:
here she is, the reason for my website. here she is, the dear teen of whom i speak so often. here she is, the smart, kind and beautiful hannah.

hannah, who is now 19, was overjoyed when i suggested we do a photoshoot to illustrate a topic which means a lot to me and even more to her: the place of women in society, especially in the light of metoo and timeâ€™s up. a topic that became important to me by necessity â€“ not for myself, actually â€“ but for them, these children that i accompany in the discovery of their lives, be it at 5, 8 or 19. what world will they live in?

the first two articles i wrote on the subjectÂ were illustrated by her younger brother and sister (from afar or with profile shots, always unrecognizable because they are underage and therefore cannot give me their consent). this is because my interrogation is about the present but mostly about the future: what is a womanâ€™s place (and a manâ€™s) in todayâ€™s world, yes, but what will their place be in the post-weinstein world? it seemed only fair that the last article of this series be illustrated by pictures of this young woman, who is undertaking a university degree which will help her understand the world she lives in from philosophical, economic and sociological perspectives, given that she believes everything is linked (and rightly so, in my opinion). so, if you want to read more about the post-weinstein era, there is a new post on the website â€“ link in bioÂ âœ¨

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

the guardian

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr

text:
iâ€™ll be speaking at this little gig on thursday
ãƒ»ãƒ»ãƒ»
are there limits to artistic freedom?

museums, and organisations representing visual artists, by and large work to support the rights of the artist. we expect artists to push  societal norms, and question issues society is grappling with. however, sometimes artists produce work going against the values of the institution, or unwittingly against minority communities. further, in the wake of the harvey weinstein charges, and the resultant #metoo movement, the personal lives of artists are being increasingly linked to their work.

at what point does the museum step in? what actions in an artist's personal life make it important for a museum to stop supporting that artist's work? and how is this decided? and if an artist creates a work that causes discomfort to certain communities - does the museum support this? or is it dependant on the community affected?

and if we oppose censorship absolutely - where does that leave us? 
thursday 8 november from 6pm - 7.30 in the lismore regional gallery event space

panelists:
* bri lee, author of 'eggshell skull' and founding editor of 'hot chicks with big brains' @bri.e.lee @hotchickswithbigbrains * esther anatolitis, executive director, national association for the visual arts (nava) @nava_visualarts @estheranatolitis * brett adlington, director, lismore regional gallery

facilitated by:
* jeanti st clair, arts journalist, documentary maker and lecturer at southern cross university 
thursday night live is a partnership event of southern cross university, scu live ideas and lismore regional gallery. @sculiveideas @southerncrossuni #thursdaynightlive #artisticfreedom #censorship #museumsperpetuatingviolence

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the start.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing for the 2016 election.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the content and more or less fake accounts - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking the responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole thing is build on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text: today america votes. many ask me what i did during my master studies in the usa. i lectured, i studied, and i published many research articles on counterculture. my mother kept one of these programmes. i wrote a paper on how a male author, thomas pynchon, created a feminist narrator in his novella â€œthe crying of lot 49â€ (1966) via its main character oedipa maas who discovers and unravels what may or may not be a world conspiracy. i read and defended this paper at a session on feminist readings of pynchonâ€™s novelsâ€. many women have risen this year revealing a wide variety of industry conspiracies about keeping women unable to advance professionally, economically and even prevented from denouncing crimes and abuse against them. i truly hope that today every single woman that has noticed that her life could have been improved, bettered or redeemed will vote to change society into an equal system for both men and women and specially for children. i believe in democracy, i believe in joint efforts and i truly hope that respect and kindness will be the pillars of the new digital age. yes. before i was a quant, a banker, a telecom engineer, an ai scientist, i was a creative writer and a researcher of societal changes. i am grateful each day for my relentless neoteny. #votetoday #womenrights #metoo #neoteny #tbts #thomaspynchon #literarycriticism

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

text:
grooming is a process used to prepare a child for sexual abuse. the aim is to gain access to a child and build a relationship with that child. before children are sexually abused, theu are often groomed by abusers.

do you know the signs? * building an emotional connection to gain a child's trust through: - attention, recognition, affection, kindness, privileges, gifts, alcohol, drugs or money. - excessive attention to one child or a small group. - establishing secrets with a child (especially something that may get the child in trouble with a parent). * the molester invests in the child and fosters guilt. * the child often believes the activity is consensual.

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the start.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.
