text:
you belong to you.
.
how many times have you let people rob you? of your time? your energy? your power?
.
how many times have you let others invade your space? your heart? your thoughts?
.
how many times have you taken low blows? laughed something off that needed challenging? allowed others to project on to you, making you think or feel that you are worth less?
.
how many times have you been taken advantage of? have you given all of yourself away and not kept anything of yourself/for yourself?
.
i get it. that still is me sometimes; going above and beyond at the expense of myself. though, with time and patience, i am relearning how to love, support and respect me, as i unfold.
.
making your world revolve around you - instead of others - doesn't have to mean being selfish. sometimes it's saying "no this isn't for me; i'm not choosing this", but sometimes it is also doing the things that fulfill you even though they might not be pleasant (e.g. caring for a sick relative because you want to).
.
ask yourself: (1) does _______(fill in blank) contribute to my expansion; mentally, physically, emotionally and spirtitually? (2) am i accepting and choosing this (my reality) right now or do i choose something different? (3) do i want to/can i change this? and if yes, how?
.
it doesn't mean saying no to your loved ones and/or things that you enjoy and are passionate about. it means saying no, when you feel that it is at the expense of yourself and your wellbeing.
.
often, we're most scared to say no to the things that we have been taught we should always be saying yes to. like family and friends. but we all need time out in this fast-paced life.
.
so get comfortable with firmly and softly saying no and make room for you, too.
.
#youbelongtoyou
.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
halloween ðŸ¿ðŸ¿ðŸ¿ðŸ¿ðŸ¿ well this was a scary surprise! a very welcome addition to the halloween universe. i dare say the best slasher film since scream 4.

we are living in a golden age of horror right now and this film was a welcome addition. anytime a movie especially horror is to be remade or prequel/sequel added this is how it should be done.

suble throwbacks to the past as well as using iconic music and credits from the original and bringing back a crowd favourite from the original? tick tick tick.

here we return to haddonsfield to revisit laurie strode 40 years after the original movie. now lets forget every other squeal ever happened.. rip halloween h20 (never forget). ok so its 40 years past laurie is alive and gone full unibomber mode. crazy hair, cabin in the woods she gone cray. but who blames her as she is preparing for the day michael returns. and well that happens to be now.

this is violent, cold, nostalgic and a strong bit of #metoo thrown in to keep it topical. this is a great horror film and if they dont make anymore atleast it didnt end the series on a low note.. now where's that nightmare on elm street sequel?

youâ€™re reading this? iâ€™m betting youâ€™re already kind. youâ€™re a woman reading this? youâ€™ve been told to be kind your whole life. telling women to be kind - again and again and again - wonâ€™t change a thing. itâ€™s like telling a supermarket to be sure to order coffee. they already do. they always will. they got the memo. 
instead, throw words around that will make change. the time for womenâ€™s #happiness and #health is now. the time for women to understand that their lives are deserving of mostly happiness is now. the time for patriarchy inducing guilt in our souls because we have not yet practiced enough kindness is over. do happy, do purpose and do you and, guess what, the kindness is built into all of that anyway. you are kind. youâ€™ve got kind, tick it off your list. done & doing. 
kindness is not the revolution that will #makewomensafe. weâ€™d be there by now, if it was. 
and if you feel compelled to remind people - especially women - to be kind, is that because someoneâ€™s fuckery is hurting you and weâ€™re trained to not talk directly to that but, by fuck, we need our plea for an end to the hurt to be heard? if it is, work hard on protecting yourself and building the reserves that let you feel the fact that your life makes a difference every single day. thereâ€™s nothing like it for kicking fuckery into perspective and freeing yourself from fear. 
kindness? as #feminists weâ€™ve got that. and the coffee. 
determinedly pursue your happiness and your purpose. repeat & grow the stuff that feels right & expansive in your soul. make time to make yourself happy and do your work. thatâ€™s not #unkind. thatâ€™s #unpatriarchy.

text:
i just want to say how much i really do believe and support male survivors. my best friend in the entire world, he's a sexual assault survivor. it was male-on-male and happened several times while he was in middle school. he thought the other male was his friend, but soon found out he was being abused. he's going through a very difficult time right now with some depressive symptoms and an unsupportive family. he's a homosexual but his family is not okay with it. he is battling ptsd, depression, and homophobia all at the same time, and i think it's pretty incredible that he can be so strong. please keep fighting and never give up. please ask for help if you need it. i love you so much and i am so sorry you are going through all of this.
#ibelievesurviors #malesurviors #metoo #rape #endrape #sexualviolence #sexualasault #rapeculture  #endrape #homophobia #mentalillnessisrealillness #love #support

text:
mgtow 101: globetrot simping ( father edition )

why do you think essence, a black female magazine posted this? you simps are so dumb you don't even know when to be offended.  bitches are hooking up with traveling men just to use them for travel lol. 90% of female travel pages that are with men who took them there. i don't bring bitches global. you only come with me to bahamas so my dad can vet your ass (when i was a simp) or you stay home and i go solo.

if you are going to travel somewhere you have never been, take your kids with you, not a gf. i can't emphasize this enough. traveling is the greatest education you can have. many men are sharing memories with women who won't appreciate it, nor be there down the line.

i see guys taking dozens of trips internationally with girlfriends, while the kids at home with the baby mama. that's fucking ass backwards. do better men, your seed comes first, in all matters. your greatest experiences should be shared with kids.

really, men should leave the daughter and bring the son, he will appreciate it more than her. i see a few travel pages with dope locations and the gf is in every picture. the pictures with the son, are local like the movies or disney world. men value yourself, value your legacy and value the future generation of men.

as a guy who is already on his third passport, i can tell you without a doubt, most of my wisdom came from overseas traveling and most importantly having the wisdom implanted early. it's different when you travel at 10 to africa and europe compared to traveling at 30. i have visited both in youth and adult age. my most valuable lessons that steered me away from the streets and stopped me from being a simp were learned as a youth traveling. the sooner you can get a global mindset the better off you will be. people with global mindsets can peep a local mindset a mile away.

don't die and have your son looking at all your photos and it hits him that his dad's greatest memories didn't include him.

you may appreciate a female's companionship but the education and bond is needed by your kids. they'll be there for your last dying breath, not the ex you wont remember from 20 years ago.

text:
november 17, 12pm â€¢ the bronx museum 
1040 grand concourse, bronx, ny 
free event â€¢ workshops â€¢ panels â€¢ film â€¢ #mlc2018
keynote: nicole dennis-benn, writer/activist

the mlc2018 is a grassroots event and a great opportunity for the bronx and new york city communities of educators, students, program administrators, and parents to learn ways to integrate books and reading into the lives of teenagers. mlc offers a mix of informative programs and creative workshops to engage young minds, strengthen literacy, and develop education strategies.

130-230pm
#metoo & the movement
black women writers conjuring in the continuum 
in 2017, the #metoo campaign amplified the voices of survivors of rape, sexual assault and harassment. though social media platforms became the route to shared survivor stories, creating heightened awareness, accountability, and solidarity in response to a pervasive rape culture that is generations-deep, black women writers have courageously confronted patriarchal violence on the page while simultaneously experiencing a spectrum of abuses and violations in our personal lives. this panel, inspired by theÂ break beat poetsâ€™ black girl magic anthology, as well as other creative collaborations and alliances, will continue this urgently important conversation. through this community dialogue,we will explore the continuum of black women writing against all that would attempt to violate our lives. we will elevate our stories, our activism, our labor, and lineage. 
panelists: jp howard, keisha-gaye anderson, and diamond sharp. facilitator: nina angela mercer

text:
10. hard commute
i left my house this morning in a car. then i walked, took a bus, caught the t and now await my train in south station. i have just consumed the five food groups of commuting in a single day. iâ€™m early so i order a cup of coffee, which is unusual for me, to snap me out of the fog that is daylight savings. when the fog clears i realize that what i thought was early christmas decorations turns out to be a massive ad campaign for erectile dysfunction. bright red signs in every crevice of the station. ed meds delivered. as a woman, and a beleaguered consumer of the current political shit storm, this bugs the crap out of me. in the wake of the kavanaugh confirmation, recurring me too wounds and the pos incel that shot up a yoga studio last weekâ€“the very last thing i want to see this morning is an ad to help dicks work better. equally irksome is the fact that insurance companies will pay to keep you erect while flaccid politicians aim to reduce womenâ€™s reproductive rights. the silver lining to all those red banners in my face is that tomorrow is election day. a word to my ladies out there, put some powder on that mushroom stamp and get out to vote. then maybe one day we might see south station festooned with banners for free birth control. iâ€™d even settle for a vaginal dryness ad, itâ€™s only fair.
